This separation prevents operational authority from becoming ownership authority.

⸻

Nature of the Licence

An ROU stewardship licence is:

• conditional — dependent on ecological protection
• revocable — failure of protection voids the licence
• non-transferable without custodial approval
• non-collateralizable — it cannot be pledged as financial security
• bounded to a defined ecological cell or set of cells

The licence exists only for the purpose of maintaining ecological continuity.

⸻

Authority Granted by ROU

The licence permits stewards to:

• operate within the declared ecological cells
• organise protection and regeneration activities
• coordinate local participation under CATOS
• maintain stewardship infrastructure
• facilitate observation and verification

These permissions exist solely to maintain ecological protection and regeneration.

⸻

Prohibitions

ROU explicitly does not grant the right to:

• sell or alienate land
• privatise ecological memory (BDR)
• treat ecological function as private property
• convert stewardship authority into extractive ownership
• override the Ecological Boolean Gate

ROU therefore functions as operational authority under ecological constraint, not property.


