⸻

Core Steward Responsibilities

Stewards are responsible for maintaining the operational conditions required for ecological continuity.

This includes:

• maintaining protection conditions across ecological cells
• ensuring continuity of Proof of Protection (PoP)
• coordinating community participation through CATOS
• facilitating witnessing through Tritestium protocols
• maintaining physical human presence within the landscape
• sustaining infrastructure required for monitoring and protection

These responsibilities exist to preserve ecological continuity across seasonal stress windows.

⸻

Steward Status

Stewards are neither owners nor employees in the conventional sense.

They function as trusted operators of ecological cells under custodial authority and independent verification.

Their legitimacy derives from:

• continuity of protection
• operational competence
• compliance with doctrine

Steward authority persists only so long as ecological protection persists.

⸻

Relationship to Ecological Truth

Stewards may:

• maintain ecological conditions
• implement protection practices
• support regeneration

Stewards may not declare ecological success.

Ecological state is determined only through:

• pentad observations
• Tritestium witnessing
• Ecological Boolean Gate resolution

This preserves the independence of ecological truth.

⸻

Steward Incentive Structure

Stewards may receive:

• livelihood support
• operational funding
• recognition within CATOS and community structures

Stewards may not:

• privatise ecological value
• claim ownership of BDR
• monetise ecological memory

Economic participation occurs only through system-defined coordination layers.

⸻

Steward Removal

A stewardship licence may be revoked if:

• Protection conditions fail
• doctrine is violated
• ecological continuity is compromised
• custodians determine stewardship failure

Revocation restores custodial authority over the ecological cell.

⸻

Foundational Principle

Stewardship authority exists only while ecological protection persists.

Authority therefore follows continuity, not title.

⸻

Closing Statement

Stewards in u-Kama do not own the land.

They hold responsibility for maintaining the conditions under which the land may continue to protect and regenerate itself.

Their legitimacy is measured not by possession, but by endurance.

